{{more footnotes|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox politician |name=William Henry Brockenbrough |image=Brockenbrough.jpg |state=Florida |district=[[Florida's at-large congressional district|at-large]] |term_start=January 24, 1846 |term_end=March 3, 1847 |predecessor=[[Edward Carrington Cabell]] |successor=[[Edward Carrington Cabell]] |office2=Member of the [[Florida Senate]] |term_start2=1840 |term_end2=1844 |predecessor2= |successor2= |office3=Member of the [[Legislative Council of the Territory of Florida]] from [[Mosquito County, Florida|Mosquito County]] |term_start3=1837 |term_end3=1842 |predecessor3=[[Charles Downing]] |successor3=[[William H. Williams (Florida politician)|William H. Williams]] |birth_date={{birth date|1812|02|23}} |birth_place=[[Virginia]] |death_date={{death date and age|1850|01|28|1812|02|23}} |death_place=[[Tallahassee, Florida]] |restingplace=Episcopal Cemetery |party=[[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] }}
'''William Henry Brockenbrough''' (February 23, 1812 – January 28, 1850) was a [[US Representative]] from Florida from 1846 to 1847, and a United States District Attorney from 1841 to 1843.<ref name="pol">The People of Florida Lawmaking</ref> He served in the [[Legislative Council of the Territory of Florida]] representing [[Mosquito County, Florida|Mosquito County]] in 1838, 1841, and in 1842 as its president.
Born in [[Virginia]], Brockenbrough studied law, was admitted to the bar and settled in [[Tallahassee, Florida]]. In 1837 he became a member of the Legislative Council of the Territory of Florida sitting as president in 1842. He became a United States [[district attorney]] 1841–1843; upon the admission of Florida as a State into the Union successfully contested as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] the election of [[Edward C. Cabell]] to the [[Twenty-ninth United States Congress]] and served from January 24, 1846, to March 3, 1847; died in Tallahassee, Florida, interred in Episcopal Cemetery.
